descript.abstract: PWD modeling sheds, at one time called allsheds2004up2.shp (earliest version called shed10). The polygons in this layer are catchments for sanitary, storm and/or combined sewer flows. These catchments are used in the hydraulic models. This layer shows the service area for PWD inside the city and outlying areas that contribute to PWD through "custody transfer" points. See "Attribute Overview" for detailed description of the shedtypes (C, S, ST, W, U).
descript.supplinf:
Edits (1/3/08 JK): - MBE12 split into MBE12 and MBE16 - MSH1B split into MSH1B and MSH2 - MLM4 split into MLM6 and MLM7 - MLM2A split into MLM2A and MLM5 - BUCKL2 renamed MLM4 - MSH1 renamed MLM3 - MLM5 outlet changed to IDR-082
5/3/07 Fixed type "ST" to "NC on shedname = TS16-NC 12/15/06 - Split D54-15, D54, & S42a-42. 10/17/06 - Fixed some duplicate polygons and mislabeled polygons. 10/13/06 The noncontributing area known as Franklin Mills was subdivided into 7 subsheds and labeled as IPOQ-120, 130, 150, 170, 188 IBLR-016B & C. The areas were added to the monitoring area 98 & 96. 10/3/06 Based on metadata fowarded from RR updated attribute table as follows: Changed shed named 'IWBR-098C' with 1.11 acre area draining to IWBR-098 to 'IWBR-050E' and it now loads to IWBR-050; Changed loading (shed R18 a stormshed used to load to IT15-022 now loads to OR18-010).RR Model Shed named 'NONE' had type 'S', it is noncontributing hence type was changed to 'NC'. Gary Martens renamed shed 'R21' to 'TR07-232' outlet may have been changed previously. 7/19/06 Copied from PWD as modelsheds, renamed to modelsheds-pwd071906. 2/3/06 Gary Martens added column "commeter" and "contract_n". 1/13/06 After the edits this coverage was converted to modelshds4 on Edison computer but sent to PWD as modelsheds. This layer was compared to modelsheds-pwd0106 which was copied from PWD and suppose to be the correct layer. However, this layer has many slivers and overlaps. So Edison's modelshds3 was used and the attributes compared and updated. The changes made so that the two layers match were shedname changes to MA_4, MBE_8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, MC_3, R11A & TS27-2104. Many outlet name changes were done too. A small overlapping square in shed wTS17-120 was removed.
12/30/05 Further refinement occurred in the area of D66, D68, TS42, TS44 & S42. Intersects with slope were done for SE & SWS. This file was sent back to PWD and is renamed as "modelsheds" for their use. 12/29/05 Exported the coverage called modelshds2 to this modelshds3 shapefile. Copied to PWD server for comparison to a newly delineated sheds that they still call modelsheds - which I've copied to this computer calling it modelshdspwd. 9/16/05 sent this layer to Sham for his use in redelineating D54. It should be stored in a common location as the good modeling shed layer.
This layer has been sent back and forth between modelers and GIS technician. Each time edits are made to the polygons by the modelers and than the GIS technician puts it through QA/QC of the topology to fix slivers and gaps. This layer should not be used until the topology has been built. The dates listed below shows the progress of this layer.
08/25/05 Found 2 more slivers that should've been removed, removed them. Even though Gary sent other subsheds on 07/25 & 07/21 I believe this is the good shed layer. The sheds gary sent in July contained slivers again.
06/02/05 Removed floating polygons east of river. 05/31/05 - recieved modelshds zipped up via email from Gary Martens 04/05/05 processed through ArcInfo checking for slivers and wholes.

overview.dsoverv: the shedtype: 'S' is separate-sanitary. These all have stormwater as well as sanitary. For the most part, the stormwater is non-contributing. When it is not, there is a copy of this shed in 'stormsheds'. 'U' unsewered is used for sheds that have houses/population but no sewers (e.g. septic tanks). 'NC' shed-type (non-contributing) is generally parkland / direct drainage sheds. 'C' combined sewer areas; These & 'ST' & 'S' are only shed types in the modelsheds coverage that contribute wet weather flow to the system. 'S' or "Sanitary" contributes through RDII. It is assumed that all sanitary sheds in this coverage have corresponding stormsheds. The stormsheds in this coverage (shed_type = 'ST') exist when there is no corresponding sanitary shed for that area; a shed that drains stormwater only (ie no sanitary flow). These are usually waterfront parking lots and such. If they send the flow directly to the river, then the attribute field 'Outlet' is blank. Otherwise, if they send stormwater flow to the combined sewer system above a regulator, then the attribute field 'OUTLET' identifies the EXTRAN NODE it loads. In addition, a sepearate shapefile called "CSOmodelstormsheds" is maintained for stormsheds that contribute to the combined sewer system and that overlap existing sanitary sheds but load to different EXTRAN NODES (i.e. have a different 'OUTLET'). For the most part, stormwater sheds do not contribute to the system, they drain directly to a body of water. These are the 'ST' sheds in 'modelsheds' with blank OUTLET attributes. There are a few exceptions, however,('TS27-3308A' with OUTLET= 'TS27-3308' is a good example) which enter the combined system and must be included in the models. If they overlap with sanitary sheds, however, which also must be included in the models, then they are maintained in the “CSOmodelstormsheds” coverage in order to maintain spatial integrity. Se, Sw, Nell, Nehl: These fields are primarily for a macro that checks the models against GIS. If we were checking the SW model, for example, it would check to see that every shed with 'True' in that column is in the model, and that everything in the model is 'True' in GIS. They are also a useful tool for viewing purposes. If, for example, we wanted to view only the sheds that are in a certain model. District: This field tells us where the dry-weather flow goes, whereas the above fields tell us if any flow (dry or wet) goes to a certain location. For example, many of the Wissahickon sheds can send flow to all three systems during wet-weather, so they are True for SE, SW, and NELL. Their dry-waether all goes to the SE, though, which would be the 'District'
overview.eaover: The attribute "Collector" and "Variable" were created so the sheds could be grouped for slope analysis. The "Variable" is a four character abbreviation of "Collector". 3 of the groupings Poquessing, Southwest Main Gravity & Upper Delaware Low Level have a slight variation of the variable. These are tagged with an I on a 3 character prefix for inside the limits of the City data. So Poquessing is POQI, Southwest Main Gravity is SMGI & Upper Delaware Low Level is UDLI.
